'''Higashi Kamo Shrine''' (ひがしかもじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Sakaide|Q855059|qid=Q855059|1=Sakaide, Kagawa}}, {{ill|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|Q161454|qid=Q161454|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} {{ill|lt=ronsha|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Hitokotonushi|Q10864079|qid=Q10864079|lt=Hitokotonushi-no-Mikoto|1=Hitokotonushi}} (ひとことぬしのみこと)
* {{ill|lt=Tamayoribime|Q56344982|qid=Q56344982|lt=Tamayorihime-no-Mikoto|1=Tamayori-hime}} (たまよりびめのみこと)

=== History ===
It is enshrined on the slope of a hill standing east of the Kamosho area. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was called names such as "Katsuragi Daimyojin," "Katsuragi no Yashiro," and "Kamosho Daimyojin"<ref name="鴨神社"/>.

According to the shrine-held ''Katsuragi Daimyojin-ki'', Atto Ōtaru asked a priest of the Kyoto {{ill|lt=Kamo Shrine|Q1306606|qid=Q1306606|lt=Kamo Shrines|1=Kamo shrines}} during the {{ill|lt=Konin|Q1373070|qid=Q1373070|1=Kōnin (era)}} era ({{ill|lt=810|Q23819|qid=Q23819|1=810}}-{{ill|lt=824|Q30353|qid=Q30353|1=824}}), and invited {{ill|lt=Takakamo Shrine|Q11673295|qid=Q11673295|lt=Takakamo no Kami|1=Takakamo Shrine}} from Katsuragi in Yamato, making it the tutelary deity of Kamosho<ref name="鴨神社"/>.

