=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|Q11634943|qid=Q11634943|lt=Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Kamo-wake-ikazuchi-no-Kami}} (わけいかづちのみこと)

=== History ===
It is enshrined southwest outside the Kamosho area. Tradition says it was the overall guardian shrine of both Kamo and Uji-be villages since its foundation and was popularly called "Kamo no Ōmori"<ref name="鴨神社"/>.

Its foundation is said to date to {{ill|lt=Konin|Q1373070|qid=Q1373070|1=Kōnin (era)}} 4 ({{ill|lt=813|Q30360|qid=Q30360|1=813}}), when Atto Ōtaru invited the deity from Yamato Province<ref name="鴨神社"/>. The shrine buildings later fell into ruin, but in the {{ill|lt=Chōryaku|Q1193519|qid=Q1193519|1=Chōryaku}} era ({{ill|lt=1037|Q19335|qid=Q19335|1=1037}}-{{ill|lt=1040|Q19342|qid=Q19342|1=1040}}), shrine family member Irie Minbu Kageaki petitioned in Kyoto and restored it<ref name="鴨神社"/>. The shrine still preserves a {{ill|lt=munafuda|Q8008834|qid=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}} board on which the characters for Chōryaku and Kageaki can actually be confirmed<ref name="鴨神社"/>.

Subsequent transitions are unclear. It is said to have burned in warfare during the Sengoku period, and a temporary hall was restored in {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 12 ({{ill|lt=1584|Q6728|qid=Q6728|1=1584}})<ref name="鴨神社"/>. This munafuda reads "Kamo Sansho Daimyojin" and includes "in ancient times each of the three shrines had its own place"<ref name="鴨神社"/>. Later, construction and repairs of shrine buildings were carried out in the Edo period.

